85. (a) One of the most noticeable characteristics in the syntax of the Letters consists in the use of the adverb with asse. This usage is frequent in colloquial Latin ol all periods. It is commonly found with adverbs ot place (pram, praesta, procul, etc), and the general and particular adverbs of manner (ito, cantra, aliter, banc, recte, tata, etc.) ς e.g.‚ sit modo recte in Hispaniis (Art. 10. 12a. 2) ς sed quidvis est melius quam sic asse ut sumus (Fam. 16. 12. 4). lu this construction esse is something more than a simple copula.

(b) More rarely, but in a few clear cases, the adverb is used in place of an attributive adjective; eg. meaa ullae privatim iniuriae (Lentulus, Fam. 12. 14. 3). Cf. also note to circumcirca, Epist. LXXV. 4, and to sic, Epist. V. 3.
